In your PHP code, the [initialization vector](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Initialization_vector) (IV) is generated with a random number generator. You may do the same with Qt. For instance:

    QByteArray iv = QByteArray(16, 0);
    for(int i=0; i&lt;16; ++i) {
        iv[i] = static_cast&lt;char&gt;(QRandomGenerator::system()-&gt;bounded(255));
    }

Instead, the [example](https://github.com/bricke/Qt-AES#example) you are following creates a string with whatever arbitrary text, and then calculates a MD5 hash of it. Using the above method is more direct, but you can do the same or [generate a random string](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3244999/create-a-random-string-or-number-in-qt4) before calculating the hash.

